SIMPLE: provide
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Provide
<hw>Pro*vide"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Provided</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Providing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>providere</ets>,
<ets>provisum</ets>; <ets>pro</ets> before + <ets>videre</ets> to see.
See <er>Vision</er>, and cf. <er>Prudent</er>, <er>Purvey</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To look out for in advance; to procure beforehand; to
get, collect, or make ready for future use; to prepare.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Provide</xex> us all things necessary.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To supply; to afford; to contribute.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bring me berries, or such cooling fruit⟦br⟧
As the kind, hospitable woods <qex>provide</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To furnish; to supply; -- formerly followed by
<xex>of</xex>, now by <xex>with</xex>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧And yet
<xex>provided</xex> him of but one.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Jer. Taylor.</au>
⟦ldquo⟧Rome . . . was well <xex>provided</xex> with corn.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Arbuthnot.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To establish as a previous condition; to stipulate;
<as>as, the contract <ex>provides</ex> that the work be well
done</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To foresee.</def> <note>[A
<xex>Latinism</xex>]</note> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>B.
Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To appoint to an ecclesiastical benefice before it
is vacant. See <er>Provisor</er>.</def> <rj><au>Prescott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Provide</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Provide
<hw>Pro*vide"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To procure
supplies or means in advance; to take measures beforehand in view of an
expected or a possible future need, especially a danger or an evil; --
followed by <xex>against or for</xex>; <as>as, to <ex>provide</ex>
against the inclemency of the weather; to <ex>provide</ex> for the
education of a child.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Government is a contrivance of human wisdom to <qex>provide</qex>
for human wants.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To stipulate previously; to condition; <as>as, the
agreement <ex>provides</ex> for an early completion of the
work</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Provided</ent>⟦br⟧
